body:
I was asked by Simon Ringuette to raise an issue here on GitHub concerning the font size Doodle answer I gave here: http://doodle.com/poll/fdm2m792kr2xx8sy

For web based applications, both pixel and points are not the best solution. The ideal font size is defined in em or rem in a web application like most of us provide, especially for better responsive compatibility.

-- Cheers, Nils

title: Addressing Label bounds and Fonts
body:
This issue is meant as a place holder for discussions regarding Labels.
It is a follow up to issue #330 and issue #458 
In particular we are interested in label :
1. bounds definition and interchange
2. Font size to be expressed in Font Points or in Pixels
3. The effect these two have together on rendering
4. Text wrapping and <cr> within labels

title: The specification is not clear on how to specify the width of the header band of a pool
body:
The specification does not document how to interchange the width (or height for vertical pools) of pools and therefore we have seen in many interchange from vendors issues on how to properly handle it.

Previously discussed solutions were:

- Consider the lanes position
- Have a fixed size (something like 40px)
- Use the label bounds

We will probably have to submit a recommendation to the RTF. We are interested in documenting here the current approach taken by vendors to propose the best solution.

title: User Task implementation attribute has an invalid value
body:
The implementaiton value at line 99, 173 and 195 cannot be WebService but should be ##WebService

Ex (line 99):

    <userTask id="_a92069f7-377b-4dbd-a1fd-1da071aabf6d"  ... implementation="WebService">

Based on the specification page 159:

This attribute specifies the technology that will be used to send and receive the Messages. Valid values are "##unspecified" for leaving the implementation technology open, "##WebService" for the Web service technology or a URI identifying any other technology or coordination protocol. A Web service is the default technology.

It should be corrected to:

    <userTask id="_a92069f7-377b-4dbd-a1fd-1da071aabf6d"  ... implementation="##WebService">

title: Empty string via non-existing attribute
body:
**Tool**
Trisotech BPMN Modeler 5.0.10

**Output of the automated checks**
```
OK     : navigateFollowingElement                 Message: bpmn:userTask[@name='Perform repair (standard level)' and @id='_d034722f-751d-4f37-a3d7-47993822e979']
FINDING: navigateBoundaryEvent                    Message: Cannot find boundary element; Parameter: bpmn:boundaryEvent[@name='' and @attachedToRef='_d034722f-751d-4f37-a3d7-47993822e979']
FINDING: checkMessageEvent                        Message: Cannot find message event definition; Parameter: bpmn:messageEventDefinition | bpmn:messageEventDefinitionRef
FINDING: navigateFollowingElement                 Message: No outgoing reference found; Parameter: bpmn:userTask[@name='Perform repair (premium level)']
OK     : navigateBookmarkedElement                Message: #document/semantic:definitions[@id='id="_5033f8b0-0396-494b-a52c-787034420443"']/semantic:process[@id='id="_8170787a-3207-434d-9bea-4787059f444f"']/semantic:userTask[@id='id="_d034722f-751d-4f37-a3d7-47993822e979"']/

```


**Trisotech Roundtrip BPMN**
```xml
<semantic:userTask id="_d034722f-751d-4f37-a3d7-47993822e979" name="Perform repair (standard level)" startQuantity="1" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" implementation="##unspecified">
....
</semantic:userTask>
...
        <semantic:boundaryEvent id="Bpmn_BoundaryEvent_LwKtwhqHEeWDuOtG0oS24A"
        attachedToRef="_d034722f-751d-4f37-a3d7-47993822e979" cancelActivity="true">
            <semantic:extensionElements>
                <w4graph:graphStyle>
                    <w4graph:basic foreground="0,0,0" collapsed="false" borderColor="255,255,255" background="0,0,0" autoResize="false"/>
                </w4graph:graphStyle>
            </semantic:extensionElements>
            <semantic:outgoing>Bpmn_SequenceFlow_-dQQwBqHEeWDuOtG0oS24A</semantic:outgoing>
            <semantic:messageEventDefinition messageRef="_6840c92f-f02c-46b3-9565-f5e5b1792ba0" id="Bpmn_MessageEventDefinition_zhREUBqHEeWDuOtG0oS24A"/>
        </semantic:boundaryEvent>
```

**Reference BPMN**
```xml
<userTask id="_d034722f-751d-4f37-a3d7-47993822e979" name="Perform repair (standard level)" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" startQuantity="1" implementation="WebService">
...
</userTask>
...
    <boundaryEvent id="Bpmn_BoundaryEvent_LwKtwhqHEeWDuOtG0oS24A"
      name=""
      attachedToRef="_d034722f-751d-4f37-a3d7-47993822e979" cancelActivity="true">
      <extensionElements>
        <w4graph:graphStyle>
          <w4graph:basic background="0,0,0" foreground="0,0,0" autoResize="false" borderColor="255,255,255" collapsed="false"/>
        </w4graph:graphStyle>
      </extensionElements>
      <outgoing>Bpmn_SequenceFlow_-dQQwBqHEeWDuOtG0oS24A</outgoing>
      <messageEventDefinition id="Bpmn_MessageEventDefinition_zhREUBqHEeWDuOtG0oS24A" messageRef="_6840c92f-f02c-46b3-9565-f5e5b1792ba0"/>
    </boundaryEvent>

```
**Analysis**
* The *name* attribute value in the reference is a zero-sized string. The *name* attribute in the tool is missing. IMHO, this is not an expected behavior, because NULL!="".
* If we decide this is acceptable, we can close #331 as well.

title: Special characters are not retained
body:
**Tool:** bpmn.io
**Version:** 0.9.2

### Reference BPMN
(excerpt)

```xml
    <userTask id="reviewInvoice" camunda:assignee="demo" camunda:formKey="app:reviewInvoice.jsf" name="Rechnung klren" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" startQuantity="1" implementation="webService">
   []
    </userTask>
```

### bpmn.io BPMN
(excerpt)

```xml
   <userTask id="reviewInvoice" name="Rechnung klren" implementation="webService" camunda:assignee="demo" camunda:formKey="app:reviewInvoice.jsf">
    []
    </userTask>
```

### Analysis

The "" character in the *name* attribute is being replaced by "". Most likely this is a codepage issue.
This happens, although both the reference and the tool XML file use the same encoding (UTF-8).
In order to verify this finding, both the reference and the tool XML have been opened explicitly as UTF-8 files.

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
```

title: Reference C.1.0: Resolution attribute missing in DI
body:
The resolution attribute is missing in <bpmndi:BPMNDiagram> element.

The missing attribute will result in tools defaulting to their own value of choice (e.g. itp-commerce = 72, trisotech = 96). While this does not affect the overall look of the diagram (as all shapes are scaled proportionally), it does make a difference to the shape-size/font-size ratio, as the font size, as I understand, is measured in points and is not scaled with respect to the resolution.

The following two images show the different results.

![c 1 0-import](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1541830/6601570/c26d63a2-c816-11e4-9e07-2b093e3ed965.png)
Resolution = 72

![c 1 0_res96](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1541830/6601611/ea0c8a3c-c816-11e4-80d4-5448e44cc390.png)
Resolution = 96


In my opinion, the following line:
```xml
<bpmndi:BPMNDiagram id="sid-78cf0368-c97e-4dea-885f-0e535c20d6c7" name="Collaboration C.1.0">
```
should be changed to this:
```xml
<bpmndi:BPMNDiagram id="sid-78cf0368-c97e-4dea-885f-0e535c20d6c7" name="Collaboration C.1.0" resolution="96">
```

"Transformation completed with warnings.

Model generation failed. Connection type 'CT_IS_PREDEC_OF_1' is not allowed."

![a 4 0_import_error](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11218291/6402083/875801c4-bdca-11e4-952a-b6263aaf0903.png)

title: End events are slightly shifted to the left
body: Compared to the reference, the end events seems to the shifted on the horizontal axis.

title: Conditions are displayed on sequence flow out of the gateways
body: We can see the conditions (${approved} for instance) being depicted on the sequence flow out of the gateways

title: Group label is not properly positioned
body: The group label is positioned to the center inside the group while the reference picture it at the top left corner outside of the group.

title: The label are slightly shifted
body:
This is especially visible on textual annotations (B.1.0 and B.2.0).

On A.4.0 we can see that the message flow labels are closer to the boundary of the lane than on the reference.

Tasks seem to have their label slightly shifted from the center also.

title: Label bound of the gateways in A.2.0 do not seem to respect the boundaries
body: The bounds of the 2 gateways of A.2.0 are not wrapping at the same position for the label which may indicate that the bound or the font-size is not respected.

title: [Tool: actiBPM] not support cyrillic characters
Name attributes are added
body:
Adonis 6.0

**Adonis BPMN**

```xml	  
      <endEvent name="End Event " id="sid-BC9AC0B6-1785-4E35-A974-7FEF1A586B9D">
	 [...]
         <incoming>sid-3019478F-48D5-4B85-95B1-E192B9BE4183</incoming>
         <inputSet/>
      </endEvent>
```
	  
**Reference BPMN**

```xml	
    <endEvent id="sid-BC9AC0B6-1785-4E35-A974-7FEF1A586B9D">
      [...]
      <incoming>sid-3019478F-48D5-4B85-95B1-E192B9BE4183</incoming>
    </endEvent>
```

Name attributes are added to endEvents although the reference bpmn has no such attribute.

title: [C.1.0 - demo] implementation of service task id="archiveInvoice"
body:
The implementation of Service Task 'archiveInvoice' is 'webService'. If the purpose is to use a web service implementation, why not use the ##webService default implementation ?

I think it whould simplify the interchange for the demo to use one of ##unspecified or ##webService.

title: [C.1.0 - demo] About the Message Start Event
body:
From an execution point of view, is it ok to start the process with a Message Start Event when we are not in a conversation context with two participant sending messages to one another ?

W4 BPMN engine for one, only accept this type of event during execution if it is the target of a Message Flow and if the source is in an executable Process in another Participant (and if the Message Flow and Participants are referenced in a Conversation and if Correlation Keys and Properties are defined, etc. as specified by the specification)
To summurise, W4 BPMN engine will not be able to instantiate a process starting with a Message Start Event if we are not in a strict collaboration/conversation context.

To simplify the modelisation I propose to replace the Message Start Event by a None Start Event, so more vendors (including W4) will be able to instantiate this process without too much trouble.

body:

**Reference BPMN**

```xml
    <semantic:outgoing>_657f30ba-0690-4a14-8b8e-d8939efcc7bd</semantic:outgoing>
    <semantic:ioSpecification>

        <semantic:dataOutput id="Dout1373655174952"/>
        <semantic:inputSet>

        </semantic:inputSet>

        <semantic:sourceRef>_3d35229f-2c75-4d5d-a066-2d14e46e442e</semantic:sourceRef>
        <semantic:targetRef>Din1373655174951</semantic:targetRef>
    </semantic:dataInputAssociation>

</semantic:serviceTask>
```
**Tool BPMN**
```xml
<serviceTask completionQuantity="1" id="_fea1c5af-6c76-403f-809e-26d476d92741" implementation="##WebService" isForCompensation="false" name="Service Task 7" startQuantity="1">
 <incoming>_6a248585-952e-40ff-82ec-b6d8f410b73a</incoming>
 <outgoing>_657f30ba-0690-4a14-8b8e-d8939efcc7bd</outgoing>
 <ioSpecification id="sid-44bab402-6fa1-4aac-9742-014e12934c43">
    <dataInput id="Din1373655174951" isCollection="false"/>
    <dataOutput id="Dout1373655174952" isCollection="false"/>
    <inputSet id="sid-771efd1f-c64c-4d25-9322-192583345b27">
       <dataInputRefs>Din1373655174951</dataInputRefs>
       <outputSetRefs>sid-71dc9ed6-930a-44b7-b8ed-09fd68cc3fed</outputSetRefs>
    </inputSet>
    <outputSet id="sid-71dc9ed6-930a-44b7-b8ed-09fd68cc3fed">
       <dataOutputRefs>Dout1373655174952</dataOutputRefs>
       <inputSetRefs>sid-771efd1f-c64c-4d25-9322-192583345b27</inputSetRefs>
    </outputSet>
 </ioSpecification>
 <dataInputAssociation id="_73afd30d-7d54-4897-9350-1f7d301ef1b2">
    <sourceRef>_3d35229f-2c75-4d5d-a066-2d14e46e442e</sourceRef>
    <targetRef>Din1373655174951</targetRef>
 </dataInputAssociation>
 <dataOutputAssociation id="_fa10ebaf-7088-4def-8cc3-d959b8876b06">

    <targetRef>_b9385abf-d293-40b7-848b-8add4db48415</targetRef>
 </dataOutputAssociation>
</serviceTask>
```

**Analysis**
* The reference BPMN has the **sourceRef** attribute pointing to the **dataOutput** element.
* The tool BPMN has the **sourceRef** attribute pointing to the **serviceTask** containing the **dataOutput**.

title: Non-existing name attribute is replaced by empty name attribute
body:
**Excerpt from reference BPMN**
```xml
<endEvent id="sid-BC9AC0B6-1785-4E35-A974-7FEF1A586B9D">
...
<endEvent id="sid-282524E6-660F-431D-8F19-1C3E9E9DE817">
```

**Excerpt from Signavio BPMN**
```xml
<endEvent id="sid-BC9AC0B6-1785-4E35-A974-7FEF1A586B9D" name="">
...
<endEvent id="sid-282524E6-660F-431D-8F19-1C3E9E9DE817" name="">
```

**Excerpt from the XPATH tool**
```
          OK     : navigateElement; Message: bpmn:task[@name='Review and document result']
          FINDING: navigateElement; Message: No node found; Parameter: bpmn:endEvent[not(@name)]
```

**Analysis**
NULL values and empty strings have different meanings in IT. As a notation commonly used in IT, these name attributes should not exist in the BPMN file generated by BPMN tools.

title: Reference A.2.1 Provide test case with different kinds of Sequence Flows
body:
As mentioned in Table 12.35, we could provide sample for:
- ("normal") Sequence Flow
- Default Sequence Flow
- Conditional Sequence Flow

Use case where I detected an interchange incompatibility:
If no conditionExpression set on a Sequence Flow and the Sequence Flow is not marked as default on outgoing reference of Task/Gateways, the Sequence Flow is  a "normal" Sequence Flow. It seems that some tools are considering it as "Default Sequence Flow" (itp Commerce, Trisotech and Signavio... I'm feeling alone :s). I think that the *default* attribute on preceding Task/Gateway is missing.
Why I want to make the difference? I want to keep the condition defined by user even if it is ignored in order that if he is not sure between default and a condition he can switch easily from one to another as we kept the conditionExpression.

Based on the specification the right behavior seems to ignore the conditionExpression and be based only on the default attribute to detect Default Sequence Flow:
Table 10.3, 10.123, 10.124, 10.125 on default attribute:
> The Sequence Flow that will receive a token when none of the conditionExpressions on  other outgoing Sequence Flows evaluate to true. The default Sequence Flow should not have a conditionExpression. Any such Expression SHALL be ignored.

I
![diagramtotestdefaultsequenceflowwithcondition-1 0](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1105127/3325776/c7c3b756-f793-11e3-84fb-cfe92abb727d.png)

>     <model:exclusiveGateway id="_jDY8EPeREeO2W5WJKwzkfQ" name="Gateway1" default="_7WRGkPeQEeO2W5WJKwzkfQ"/><model:sequenceFlow id="_7WRGkPeQEeO2W5WJKwzkfQ" name="" sourceRef="_jDY8EPeREeO2W5WJKwzkfQ" targetRef="_7TL9YPeQEeO2W5WJKwzkfQ">      <model:conditionExpression xsi:type="model:tFormalExpression" id="_kZ1xofeREeO2W5WJKwzkfQ" evaluatesToTypeRef="java:java.lang.Boolean">true</model:conditionExpression>    </model:sequenceFlow>

The litigious case is in green and I put my understanding of the right value:

title: BoundaryEvents not contained in Lanes
body:
Model B.2.0 contains no FlowNodeRefs for Boundary Events. That raises two questions:

1. Are the Boundary Events visible?
a) yes, because they are attached to Flow Nodes that are assigned to Lanes
b) no, because they is not assigned to Lanes
c) It depends solely on the DI

2. Is the test case valid with respect to the BPMN 2.0 spec?
a) yes, because a Boundary Event can not be used without the Flow Node to which it is attached and it would be redundant to add an extra FlowNodeRefs.
b) no, because if a Process contains Lanes, then all Flow Nodes must be assigned to Lanes.

title: Specification of 'ping' type service task
body:
Background 
---------------
This is an attempt to merge #181 and #182 including feedback thus far received into a single problem definition and alternative possible solutions. 

A 'ping' type service arose in discussions of serviceTask interchange in an attempt to simplify the many challenges to just those where no data is involved. 

In common with the wider approach of the working group we also want to start from simple examples to maximise the amount of interchange that can be achieved and then use that as a beach-head from which to build. 

Relevant references to the spec
----------------------------------------
* From p213 (PDF p243): 
    
```
    [An ioSpec contains] An optional reference to 
    the Data Inputs of the InputOutputSpecification. If the 
    InputOutputSpecification defines no Data Input, it means no 
    data is REQUIRED to start the Activity. This is an ordered set.  
```

* This statement is made for service tasks on p158 (PDF p.188):

```
    In addition the following constraints are introduced 
    when the Service Task references an Operation: The Service Task has 
    exactly one inputSet and at most one outputSet. It has a single Data 
    Input with an ItemDefinition equivalent to the one defined by the 
    Message referenced by the inMessageRef attribute of the associated 
    Operation. If the Operation defines output Messages, the Service Task 
    has a single Data Output that has an ItemDefinition equivalent to the 
    one defined by the Message referenced by the outMessageRef attribute 
    of the associated Operation.
```

Summary of discussion 
-----------------------------
* The first quote suggested that it would be possible to fully specify the serviceTask in [A.1.1](https://github.com/bpmn-miwg/bpmn-miwg-test-suite/blob/master/Reference/A.1.1.bpmn) by the following snippet. Note that it omits not only the current ioSpecification/inputset/dataInputRefs that repeat the dataInput but the ioSpecification in its entirety:
```
        <semantic:serviceTask implementation="##WebService" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" startQuantity="1" name="Task 2" id="task2" operationRef="operation1">
            <semantic:incoming>_1a66ccd9-a80c-44bc-a06f-a684b8370443</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:outgoing>_725826e9-0e8b-4cb4-842b-e0279515d821</semantic:outgoing>
        </semantic:serviceTask>
```

* However the second quote appears to block that approach, but thus far no one has spoken in defence of the constraint. Therefore the proposal is to 'correct' (relax) this constraint in some way. 

Possible solutions
-------------------------
The following alternatives are offered for discussion with the view that one be selected as the proposal of the group:

1. Do nothing, the constraint is needed (presumably by some fact not yet raised). 
1. Make the constraint apply only to ##WebServices. 
1. Remove the constraint altogether for all values of the implementation attribute since currently legitimate web services cannot be called (both the ping-type and also Out-Only message exchange patterns).

title: XML Schema of 'Definition' element on page 54 lacks name attribute
body: In the testing, it was shown that the "name" of the test file, residing in the name attribute of the definitions element of the reference model's BPMN XML, was moved to the name attribute of process element in the BPMN XML generated by the tool.  The use of "name" for a process in tooling is not consistently realized across vendors, even though the attribute inherits from the callableElement class per the meta model - see Figure 10.3 for Process Details and Table 10.1 for Process Attributes and Model Associations in pp. 147-148 in the spec document (pp. 177-178 in the PDF document).  While I suspect that this can give rise to interchange issues as it did here, the comparison revealed an error in the spec that should be corrected - namely, the schema for definitions, which is missing the name attribute, per Table 8.3 Definition of XML Schema on p. 54 of the spec document (p. 84 of the PDF document), even though the meta model requires it, per Figure 8.4 for Definitions on p. 51 in the spec document (p. 81 in the PDF document), as does the associated table, per Table 8.1 for Definitions Attributes and Model Associations on p. 52 in the spec document (p. 82 in the PDF document).  A minor point, but I wonder if this contributes to the confusion over process name, file name, and definitions name, which seems to be left to the tooling community to resolve.

title: Changes to definitions and process elements in BPMN XML file - Blueworks Live (April 2014 Release)_Test A.1.0+A.2.0_Import+Export+Roundtrip
body: Changes that are interchange issues are the addition of processType (set to "Private") and name (set to the name of the process, which is the same as the file name) attributes of the process element.  These attributes are not in the reference import file, and the processType attribute is set to something other than its default (which is "None" and would otherwise be presumably understood) while name is not consistently included in BPMN XML serializations by modeling tools (even though it is inherited from CallableElement).  The main distinction here is that the reference model file has the "name" used present in the definitions for the reference model (semantic:definitions id="_1373649849716" name="A.1.0"), while the roundtrip and export files have the "name" used present in the process name attribute (process isExecutable="false" processType="Private" name="A.1.0" id="bpmn-4a8d7768-b5ec-49c1-b3eb-b0281b85afdf").  There is no name attribute in the definitions element of the roundtrip and export files (definitions xmlns="http://www.omg.org/spec/BPMN/20100524/MODEL" id="bpmn-922d8a9f-83c6-48eb-896d-463ae1888c73"), which is also a change from the reference model.  Finally, there are imports in the roundtrip and export files for "Resources" and "Glossaries" that presumably allow links to entries in those lists (if populated in the tool), and are included along with the BPMN XML file in a zip file.

title: Representation of lanes and related extensions in the BPMN XML file - Blueworks Live (April 2014 Release)_Test A.1.0+A.2.0_Import+Export+Roundtrip
body:
This is a known feature of this IBM tool for modeling processes in BPMN.  Some aspects are not interchange problems while others are.

One aspect that is not an interchange issue is the addition of the "Milestone" concept in the tool as a means of sectioning the process into meaningful segments.  While seemingly done as a legitimate extension (xmlns:ns2="http://www.ibm.com/bpm/Extensions"), it is nonetheless essentially a vertically-oriented lane, each one of which can be named separately.  One "Milestone" must be present in the model, though - at least according to what the tool allows the user to do.  The XML for this addition as its own flow container is presented below.
![ibmmilestoneextensions](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4049289/2847520/6b149562-d0af-11e3-9a8e-e8b336eedc45.png)

The aspect that is an interchange issue is the introduction of a laneSet but no lane into the BPMN XML, which happens in the roundtrip and export files.  However, it is represented with only a single tag and no flowNodeRefs are included, so it is unclear how the tool knows to associate flowNodes with the lane container as shown below (laneSet id="bpmn-885268d8-28d6-4bde-a20d-93568e1effce"/).  In addition, the name for this lane is shown in the tool as "Unassigned" (the default value) but is not shown anywhere in the BPMN XML.  However, none of this is the case if an actual name is entered for the lane in the tool, so this structure seems a placeholder until the lane is actually named, which then creates the expected XML structures.  This quirk of the tool may create problems for other tools to exchange simple models without lanes (and pools can't be done anyway).

title: Lack of DI component in BPMN XML file - Blueworks Live (April 2014 Release)_Test A.1.0+A.2.0_Import+Export+Roundtrip
body:
This is a known feature of IBM products for modeling processes in BPMN - namely that these tools have their own auto-layout feature that constructs the diagram from the semantic elements, their intended behaviors, and some internal heuristics for drawing the diagram.  Any DI component is ignored on import, and is not created on export.  However, the A.1.0 file is simple enough so that the generated diagram matched the reference model.  It is unclear if more complicated models will yield similar results, especially because this tool (Blueworks Live) supports only a subset of elements (e.g., not all event types, no boundary events, etc.).  However, an unnamed horizontal lane is added along with a vertically-oriented lane-like item called a Milestone, as shown below in the two pairs of results for A.1.0 and A.2.0:

versus what is true for the reference model

title: BPMNEdge should use sourceElement and targetElement attributes only by exception
body:
The use of sourceElement and targetElement attributes on the BPMNEdge element has several different implementations: 

1. Activiti, Bonitasoft, ITP, Trisotech (Reference): do _not_ add source or target attributes to edge at all
2. Camunda, Signavio, Yaoqiang: _do_ add attributes and they all point to the id of the bpmn element not the diagram element. 
3. Adonis, W4: _do_ add attributes and they point to the DI element

My first reading was that the diagram on p400 of the spec suggested that group 3 have the correct reading though of course the XSD cannot (well does not anyway) enforce this. There may be a small problem in that this sentence on p381 gives some comfort to the group 2 tools: 

```
When rendering a BPMN diagram, the correct depiction of a BPMNShape or BPMNEdge
depends mainly on the referenced BPMN model element [bpmnElement] and its 
particular attributes and/or references.
```

However, I think the definitive sentence is on page 410 where it states (_*my emphasis*_): 
```
The target [targetElement] and source [sourceElement] of a BPMNEdge _*may*_ be 
redefined when the depiction of the source or target of the edge is different than the 
target [targetRef] and source [sourceRef] of the referenced model element 
[bpmnElement] (e.g., Message flow finishing on the border of a black box Pool or a 
collapsed Sub-Process rather than the actual Flow Node within the Pool or Sub-Process). 
In such case, the targetElement and/or sourceElement of the BPMNEdge must point to 
the appropriate BPMNShape or BPMNEdge. 
```

As such, I believe group 1 have the correct interpretation in the spirit of the document, though the use of 'redefined' rather than 'defined' may be read to support group 2 and as such the spec is ambiguous. Both readings tend IMO to undermine my first impression looking only at the diagram on p400, though I note that only the group 1 reading is compatible with the diagram and that is why I believe it is the correct one.  

## Proposal
- Endorse the reading of group 1 as correct by proposing 'defined' in place of 'redefined' on p410 of spec. 
- Add an enhancement request to other usages in the test automation tools.

title: Connection of Throwing and Catching Link Events ambiguous
body:
The BPMN spec is ambiguous about the connection of throwing and catching Link Events. I see two possible interpretations:

1. Throwing and Catching Link Events are correlated using the mandatory attribute **name** and the attributes **source** and **target** are just optional similar to **incoming** and **outgoing**. 
2. Throwing and Catching Link Events are correlated using the attributes **source** and **target**.

After further investigation, I discovered that the BPMN 2.0 Finalization Task Force intended to introduce the attributes 'source' and 'target' to avoid the correlation via names. See also [OMG Issue 14816](http://www.omg.org/issues/issue14816.txt), [BPMN 2.0 FTF Report](http://www.omg.org/cgi-bin/doc?dtc/2010-05-01) and [BPMN 2.0 FTF Report Verification Site](http://omg-tf.appspot.com/tf/verify/BPMN-2.0/10).

Here is the resolution that all FTF members accepted:
![resolution-of-omg-issue-14816](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/40038/715169/fa3f1db4-df12-11e2-8efb-fa96078199af.png)

This is what's in the final BPMN 2.0 specification:
![link-event-definition-class-diagram-of-bpmn-2 0](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/40038/715184/403a0572-df13-11e2-9815-e7a45c96f472.png)

So it looks like **source** and **target** are meant to be used for link correlation. However, this raises further questions:

1. Why is the **name** attribute still there?
2. Does this new mechanism break backwards compatibility with BPMN 1.x?
3. How did vendors actually implement it in their current implementation?

title: Yaoqiang's usage of /definitions/BPMNDiagram/@documentation attribute
body:
In reference to our discussion of the 4th Sept 13 about the /definitions[1]/BPMNDiagram[1]/@documentation issue highlighted by the the xml-compare tool in the Yaoqiang example (http://tools.bpmn-miwg.cloudbees.net/xml-compare/Yaoqiang%202.2.6-A-roundtrip.html), I have come across the following information in the BPMN spec:

On page 491, the spec states that the '@documentation' attribute of the BPMNDiagram element is used for "the documentation of the diagram". This conflicts with Yaoqiang's usage as a storage for style information.

title: absence of default expressionLanguage attribute is not a semantic difference
body:
As may be seen here: http://tools.bpmn-miwg.cloudbees.net/xml-compare/Yaoqiang%202.2.6-A-roundtrip.html, when one tool specifies the expressionLanguage (which has a default value) but the other does not this is highlighted by the xml-compare tool. 

After discussion at the meeting 4th Sept 13 we recommend that the tool hide this difference if possible.

title: Conflict in BPMN Import location attribute requirement
body:
In the BPMN 2.0 specification page 54, the table 8.2 describes the attributes of the *Import* element. It describes the location attribute with a cardinality of **[0..1]**.

Later in table 8.4, the same *location* attribute is the xsd schema is defined as **required**.

```xml
    <sequenceFlow id="_e16564d7-0c4c-413e-95f6-f668a3f851fb" sourceRef="_93c466ab-b271-4376-a427-f4c353d55ce8" targetRef="_ec59e164-68b4-4f94-98de-ffb1c58a84af">
    </sequenceFlow>
```

**Interpretation:**
* There are no *incoming* and *outgoing* elements within the flow nodes. Therefore, all navigational tests cause findings.
* While it seems there is no semantical information missing (everything is defined in the sequence flow elements), there still is a difference to the reference file.
* This affects all tests.

title: Link Event Definition: Table 10.98 inconsistent with XSD and MM
body:
Cardinalities of source and target in Table 10.98 are inconsistent with BPMN's XML Schema and UML Meta-Model:

Table 10.98 on page 270 (PDF 300) says:
- sources: LinkEventDefinition [1..*]
- target: LinkEventDefinition [1]

XML Schema says:
```xml
<xsd:element name="source" type="xsd:QName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
<xsd:element name="target" type="xsd:QName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
```
UML Meta-Model says for both:
Lower Bound: 0
(see also Figure 10.73 on page 262 (PDF 292))

**Proposal**:
Change Table 10.98 on page 270 (PDF 300) into:
- sources: LinkEventDefinition [0..*]
- target: LinkEventDefinition [0..1]

title: B.2.0 Violation of EventBasedGateway Constraint
body:
Hi,
I'm currently evaluating the eclipse BPMN2 modeler and in doing so I spotted a spec violation in the reference model B.2.0:
The "Event Base Gateway 3" links to a Message Intermediate Catch Event and to a Receive Task. This is not allowed by the Spec (p. 298):

    "Event-Based Gateways are configured by having outgoing Sequence Flows target
    an Intermediate Event or a Receive Task in any combination[...] except that: 
    If Message Intermediate Events are used in the configuration, then Receive 
    Tasks MUST NOT be used in that configuration and vice versa."

Kind regards,
Matthias

title: B.1.0. Pool and Lane bounds
body:
The BPMN spec requires that a lane shape extend the full length of its enclosing pool. This, however, is hard to achieve as BPMNDI does not specify the size of the pool label box. Since tool vendors are free to define whatever size they like, pools and lanes will hardly ever be aligned.

Bruce Silver and I have discussed this issue a while back and we then agreed that the best thing to do would be to export the inner bounds of a pool instead. That way lanes will always be perfectly aligned and there is no risk of the separating label line crossing another shape that was drawn too close to the borders.

Bruce Silver also recommends this approach in his book 'BPMN Method & Style': "...in BPMN-I the dc:Bounds/@x value of horizontal lane and pool shapes should be the same. (p. 206)
